\section*{Abstract} 
%Aim 200-300 words --- New Phyt 200 GCB 300
% Currently 201
The timing of major life history events, such as the start of growth or reproduction, often span weeks or months within a community due to species' different timings. Theory suggests this variation comes from species partitioning time to reduce competition for resources. Species shared evolutionary history, however, may moderate such potential effects. Adding to this complexity, timings vary across environments as they are often controlled by responses to environmental cues---such as temperature and daylength. 
