Here we test how environmental cues and evolutionary relationships shape species-level variation in phenology of forest communities in North America. Leveraging two growth chamber studies that vary chilling, forcing and photoperiod, we use a Bayesian phylogenetic approach to estimate budburst responses across 47 species and sites. We collected samples of 47 woody plant species from four sites, in eastern and western North America, with pairs of sites on each coast spanning 4-6$^{\circ}$ latitude. Our dataset includes the diverse assemblages of tree and shrubs found in eastern and western deciduous forests, allowing us to explore differences across both sites and functional groups (e.g., understory shrubs versus canopy trees)  in eastern versus western forests. %We predicted that sites would differ in species budburst cues, given the differences in the dominant forest composition between sites, reflecting differences in the forest architecture and resource availability. 
