While our findings have applications to plant communities, our analytical approach is widely applicable to forecasting species responses to climate change. The phylogenetic model we used here could be easily applied to other phenological events, such as egg laying or species emergence in the spring, to assess the relative importance of cues and offers the opportunity to study suites of species from across the tree of life. This combination of species-rich and community-wide approaches with phylogenetic relationships can help understand the complex relationships between species evolutionary history and current ecological processes that are shaping spring phenology under our changing climate.

